##People who recover may still carry the virus, study says

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Wu Yi is a reporter for the paper

On 27 February, Jama, the leading International Medical Journal, published a research paper entitled "Positive RT-PCR Test Results in Patients Recovered From COVID-19" .

The study found four COVID-19 patients who met criteria for discharge or quarantine and were positive for COVID-19 nucleic acid 5 to 13 days later by real-time reverse polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) . The findings suggest that at least some of the recovered patients may still be carriers of the virus and that discharge criteria may need to be reassessed. In view of the positive result of nucleic acid test found during the follow-up consultation, Guo Yanhong, inspector of the Medical Administration and Hospital Authority of the National Health Commission, said at a press conference of the joint prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council on February 28, "surveillance showed that none of these patients were able to pass on the virus to others, and some of them tested negative for the new coronavirus nucleic acid, " she said, noting that the new coronavirus was a new virus, its pathogenic mechanism, the whole picture of the disease and the characteristics of the course of the disease need to be further understood.

The corresponding authors are Xu Haibo, MD, director of Imaging Department, Department of Radiology, Zhongnan Hospital, Wuhan University, and Li Yirong, MD, director of laboratory.

Previous studies of 2019 coronavirus disease (COVID-19) have focused on the epidemiological, clinical and radiological characteristics of patients diagnosed with the infection, the study notes.

The study was conducted at Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University from January 1 to February 15,2020. One inpatient and three COVID-19 patients (all patients were medical personnel) were treated at Zhongnan Hospital of Wuhan University, real-time reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) was performed to test the COVID-19 nucleic acids to see if they could be restored to work. Discharge from hospital or quarantine must meet all of the following conditions: (1) normal body temperature lasting more than 3 days, (2) remission of respiratory system symptoms, (3) significant improvement of acute exudative lesions on chest CT images, (4) the results of the two consecutive RT-PCR tests were negative and the interval between the two tests was at least 1 day.

Initially, using the previously described method, medical professionals performed RT-PCR tests on throat swabs in four patients who were infected in COVID-19. Two of them were male, ranging in age from 30 to 36. All 3 patients had fever, cough, or both symptoms. One patient was initially asymptomatic and underwent a thin-slice CT scan due to exposure to infected patients. All the patients were positive by RT-PCR, and CT images showed ground-glass opacity or mixed ground-glass opacity. The disease is mild to moderate in severity.

The hospital provided antiviral therapy (75 MG Oseltamivir orally every 12 hours) to four patients. All the clinical symptoms and CT images of 3 patients have returned to normal. The CT images of the fourth patient showed a fine ground-glass opacity. All 4 patients were negative for 2 consecutive RT-PCR, and the time from symptom onset to recovery was 12 to 32 days.

The 4 patients were discharged or suspended isolation after meeting the conditions for discharge, which were negative for RT-PCR, clinical features and normal chest CT findings, but were required to continue isolation at home for 5 days. They were retested by RT-PCR 5 to 13 days later and all were positive. All patients then underwent three repeated RT-PCR tests over the next four to five days, all of which were positive. In addition, the hospital also used kits from other manufacturers to test these patients with RT-PCR results were positive. The patients remained asymptomatic after clinical examination, and the chest CT findings were unchanged compared with previous images. The patient reported no exposure to anyone with respiratory symptoms (after discharge) and no family infection.

The four COVID-19 patients who met the criteria for discharge or quarantine (no clinical symptoms or radiological abnormalities, and both were negative by RT-PCR) were found to be positive by RT-PCR 5 to 13 days later. This suggests that at least some of the recovered patients may still be carriers.

The study suggests that although no family members were infected, these reported patients were medical professionals and received special care during home isolation, current discharge or suspension of quarantine standards and ongoing patient management may need to be reassessed.

The study was limited to a small number of patients with mild to moderate infections, the paper said. Further studies should be carried out for non-health-care professionals in patients with more severe infections after discharge from hospital or discontinuation of isolation. Longitudinal studies of more patients will help to understand the prognosis of the disease.

Why can the patient appear after discharge"Fu Yang"phenomenon, how should deal with? On February 27, the Guangzhou Medical University held a special news briefing on epidemic prevention and control, said Chinese Academy of Engineering Zhong Nanshan, a senior expert group leader of the National Health Commission and an academician of the Chinese Academy of Engineering, it may be related to many factors, such as its own situation, nucleic acid detection, detection reagents, detection methods, sampling methods may have an impact on the positive rate.

Zhong Nanshan points out that Emerging Infectious Diseases pneumonia is a disease that can not be definitively ruled out. As long as the recovered patient produces enough antibodies, there will be no re-infection. It remains to be seen whether it will spread to others. If they test positive in isolation at home, they need to be retested 24 hours later, and if both times are positive, they need to see a doctor.

And on February 28, at a press conference of the joint prevention and Control Mechanism of the State Council, Guo Yanhong, an inspector of the Medical Administration and Hospital Authority of the National Health Commission, said that with the increasing number of cured patients, in order to understand patients'rehabilitation status after discharge from hospital in a timely manner, the National Health Commission issued a document on Feb. 17, requiring follow-up and health management of discharged patients. During this process, some provinces reported cured discharged patients and found positive nucleic acid test during the follow-up visit. The National Health Commission organized experts to study the problem, while also strengthening the continuous monitoring of these cases.

"surveillance showed that there was no further transmission of the virus to other patients, and some patients tested negative for the new coronavirus nucleic acid, " Guo said, adding that the new coronavirus is a new virus, its pathogenic mechanism, the whole picture of the disease and the characteristics of the course of the disease need to be further understood.

To further strengthen the management of discharged patients, Guo said, 14 days of medical observation is now required, and follow-up, health monitoring and health guidance are strengthened in the implementation of 14 days of medical observation, at the same time, the Organization of experts to conduct further research on this situation, the occurrence of the disease, development, the whole process of further understanding.

According to the interpretation of the sixth edition of the COVID-19, after discharge from hospital, patients should continue to undergo self-health monitoring for 14 days, wear a mask and live in a well-ventilated single room, reduce close contact with family members. It is suggested that follow-up visit and follow-up visit should be made in the 2nd and 4th week after discharge.

A number of earlier announcements have also called for patients discharged from the hospital to be re-isolated observation. On February 22, the new crown pneumonia (NCP) epidemic prevention and Control Headquarters in Wuhan issued a notice saying that from today, patients discharged from the hospital after being cured of NCP should be placed under a 14-day free rehabilitation isolation and medical observation at designated places. At the end of the observation period, the quarantine shall be lifted if the physical condition meets the conditions. The next day, the Huangshi also announced that it would do the same.
